text.tspan: CAPTION: Hypothesized neural implementation of the indirection mechanism described in the paper. Convergent projections from multiple stripes
constitute the receptive field for a meta-type stripe that represents and maintains only stripe-level (i.e., ``variable'') information, without content-
level (``value''), information. E.g., the three ``regular'' PFC stripes shown (macrocolumns) are specialized for maintaining different kinds of
information, e.g., letters, numbers, and shape-labels. Macrocolumns function like "variables" while their constituent microcolumns function like
current "values" for those variables. Here a letter `D' has just been stored in a letter-storing PFC stripe (red cell bodies in left most stripe). This
activation is projected to both cortex and thalamus, in this case to a meta-type stripe whose variable description might be something like ``Stripe
active at time rank 1.'' Note that it does not matter which letter was gated in; because of the convergent projections to both cortex and
thalamus, only the stripe identity (``letter storing stripe'') is communicated to the meta-type stripe. Contiguously, a gating signal is computed
by the basal ganglia (BG) to gate the meta-type stripe into maintenance mode (green inputs to the thalamus). Note that the BG gating signal
is non-specific not only as to ``regular'' stripe content (e.g., `D' vs. `A'), but also as to which of the stripes in the meta-stripe's receptive field
is gated (e.g., "letter-storing vs. "number-storing''). Which thalamic relay cell (TRC) gets active is determined by which one(s) currently have
driving inputs. No driving inputs, no TRC firing --- even when the gate is opened. KEY: II, IV, Vb = cortical laminae; SNr/GPi = substantia nigra, pars
reticulata, globus pallidus, internal segment; MD = mediodorsal nucleus of the thalamus.
